            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this pro forma income statement calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool builds a 3-year projected income statement (also
                called a pro forma P&amp;L) starting from your latest actual
                revenue and a few key assumptions. It is designed to be fast
                enough for a pitch deck, but structured enough for serious
                planning.
              </p>

              <h3>Key line items and formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Revenue forecast</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( R_0 \) be your base (Year 0) revenue and \( g_t \) the
                  growth rate for year \( t \).
                </p>
                <p>
                  Year 1 revenue: \( R_1 = R_0 \times (1 + g_1) \)<br />
                  Year 2 revenue: \( R_2 = R_1 \times (1 + g_2) \)<br />
                  Year 3 revenue: \( R_3 = R_2 \times (1 + g_3) \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>2. Cost of goods sold (COGS)</strong></p>
                <p>COGS is modeled as a percentage of revenue:</p>
                <p>\( \text{COGS}_t = R_t \times \text{COGS\%}_t \)</p>
                <p><strong>3. Gross profit</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Gross Profit}_t = R_t - \text{COGS}_t \)</p>
                <p><strong>4. Operating expenses (Opex)</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Opex}_t = R_t \times \text{Opex\%}_t \)</p>
                <p><strong>5. EBITDA</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{EBITDA}_t = \text{Gross Profit}_t - \text{Opex}_t \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>6. EBIT (Operating income)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  For simplicity, this template assumes depreciation &amp;
                  amortization are included in Opex:
                </p>
                <p>\( \text{EBIT}_t = \text{EBITDA}_t \)</p>
                <p><strong>7. Pre-tax income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Pre-tax Income}_t = \text{EBIT}_t - \text{Interest}_t
                  \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>8. Income tax</strong></p>
                <p>If pre-tax income is positive:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Tax}_t = \text{Pre-tax Income}_t \times \text{Tax
                  Rate} \)
                </p>
                <p>Otherwise, tax is set to 0.</p>
                <p><strong>9. Net income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Net Income}_t = \text{Pre-tax Income}_t -
                  \text{Tax}_t \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Simple vs detailed mode</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple mode</strong> uses a single COGS % and Opex %
                  for all forecast years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Detailed mode</strong> lets you override COGS %, Opex
                  %, and interest expense for each year individually, while
                  still using the same revenue growth assumptions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What is a pro forma income statement?</h2>
              <p>
                A pro forma income statement is a projected profit and loss
                statement that shows what your revenue, expenses, and net income
                <em>could</em> look like in future periods under a set of
                assumptions. It is widely used for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Startup and small business financial models</li>
                <li>Investor pitch decks and fundraising</li>
                <li>Loan applications and banking relationships</li>
                <li>Evaluating new products, markets, or pricing changes</li>
                <li>Scenario analysis (best case, base case, downside)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Typical structure of a pro forma income statement</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Revenue</strong> (by product, segment, or total)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cost of goods sold</strong> (direct costs tied to
                  revenue)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gross profit</strong> and
                  <strong>gross margin</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Operating expenses</strong> (sales &amp; marketing,
                  R&amp;D, G&amp;A)
                </li>
                <li><strong>EBITDA</strong> and/or <strong>EBIT</strong></li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest expense</strong> and other non-operating
                  items
                </li>
                <li><strong>Income tax expense</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Net income</strong> (profit after tax)</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use this calculator effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start from reality.</strong> Use your latest 12-month
                  revenue as the base year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose realistic growth rates.</strong> Cross-check
                  with your historical growth and industry benchmarks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set COGS % and Opex %.</strong> If you have historical
                  financials, compute these ratios from your actual income
                  statement.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Model debt costs.</strong> Enter your expected annual
                  interest expense based on existing and planned loans.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Run multiple scenarios.</strong> Duplicate your
                  assumptions for conservative, base, and aggressive cases.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Limitations and good practice</h3>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on the income statement only. For a complete
                financial model you should also consider:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Cash flow timing (collections, payments, working capital)
                </li>
                <li>Capital expenditures and depreciation schedules</li>
                <li>Balance sheet items such as inventory and receivables</li>
                <li>Financing structure (equity vs debt)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always document your assumptions and keep a versioned copy of
                your model so you can explain changes over time to investors,
                lenders, or internal stakeholders.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I export this pro forma income statement?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Use the “Download CSV” button to export the 3-year table.
                You can then open it in Excel, Google Sheets, or any spreadsheet
